A valid, but non-existant e-mail address has been entered in the "To: " field. 


How do you find this out after filesender said: "Your file has been sent."? 

Normally an e-mail containing an error message will be sent to the e-mail address in "Return-Path:" field. 

In my setup this is by default www-data@belnet.be, i.e. the apache daemon, which is useless, as it should be to the {filefrom} e-mail address. 

Changing the value of this parameter ranges from easy to tough depending on the underlying system used. 


Proposal to solve in ../filesender_0.1.9/classes/Mail.php: 


After the "$headers"-section, add the line: $returnpath = "-r".$mailobject['filefrom']."\n"; 


Change line 49: if (mail($to, $subject, $body, $headers)) { 

To: if (mail($to, $subject, $body, $headers, $returnpath)) { 


With this change the sender will always get the e-mail with the error message (if there is one)

I noticed that admins need to be entered like this:

$config['admin'] = 'admin1,admin2';

If you have a space between two admins, like this:

$config['admin'] = 'admin1, admin2';

admin2 won't have admin access.  Xander, can you confirm this problem?  If it turns out to be a problem, it would be nice to know whether this is something that is fixable or that we need to document in the reference guide.

