    img.src = 'http://example.com/any_small_image_use_on_web_page.gif';
}
}

Two minor problems:

1) this gives a http-request that results in a 404 not found to an *unrelated* existing website
2) when filesender is served over https it leads to a 'partially encrypted page' warning

I tried to replace the image link with something like 'assets/true.png' but that breaks the intended purpose of the function :(

Currently you need to define the filesender installation urls at multiple locations in the config.php file:

	$config['site_url'] = 'http://siteurl/cloudstor/'; // URL to Filesender
	$config['site_simplesamlurl'] = 'http://siteurl/simplesamlphp/';
	$config['site_downloadurl'] = 'http://siteurl/cloudstor/files/';
	$config['site_logouturl'] = 'http://siteurl/cloudstor/logout.php';

I'm not sure why the hostname is required, since filesender could also work with relative links/redirects. The only usecase I could think of is when for example the files are hosted on a different machine/virtualhost. Anyway, it is a good idea to specify the hostname only once, this is less typing and less error prone. I'm not sure what is 'cloudstor' also, I think that is a test machine something that slipped into the release.

