Since moving the supported/not supported text to a tooltip under the HTML5 logo the text in the two related language tags is shown in raw form, for example the <br /> tags but also <b> and html entities like &iexcl.

The relevant code:
www/index.php:                  $("#html5image").attr("title","<?php echo lang("_HTML5Supported"); ?>");
www/index.php:                  $("#html5image").attr("title","<?php echo lang("_HTML5NotSupported"); ?>");

And some 'broken' examples from the current language files (the first one spotted by Wendy):

language/en_AU.php:$lang["_HTML5NotSupported"] = "Uploads over 2GB<br />not supported!";
language/hu_HU.php:$lang["_HTML5NotSupported"] = "2GB-nál nagyobb fájl feltöltése<br /><b>nem támogatott</b>!";                   
language/es_ES.php:$lang["_HTML5Supported"] = "&iexcl;Permite archivos <b>mayores</b> de 2GB!";

We could solve this by changing the varous language tags and restrict their content to unencoded UTF8 characters (no html entities allowed) and strip all html tags.

Or (if possible???) we could use some decoding/parsing function before displaying the two involved language tags (either in PHP or javascript?) Chris, would that be a possiblity?
